  "Plan A has a $300/month premium and $500 deductible. Plan B has a $200/month premium and $2,000 deductible. If you expect $3,000 in medical expenses this year, which plan costs less total?": "",
  "Plan B — $4,400 total": "",
  "They cost exactly the same": "",
  "Plan A — $4,100 total": "",
  "Plan B — $4,100 total": "",
  "Plan A: $300 x 12 + $500 deductible = $4,100. Plan B: $200 x 12 + $2,000 deductible = $4,400. With $3,000 in expected expenses, Plan A saves $300 despite the higher monthly premium.": "",
  "Sarah has health insurance with a $1,500 deductible, 80/20 coinsurance, and $6,000 out-of-pocket maximum. She has a surgery costing $25,000. How much does she pay out of pocket?": "",
  "$5,000": "",
  "$6,000": "",
  "$6,200": "",
  "$25,000": "",
  "She pays the $1,500 deductible first. Remaining $23,500: she owes 20% = $4,700. But $1,500 + $4,700 = $6,200 exceeds the $6,000 out-of-pocket max. So she pays the $6,000 cap and insurance covers the rest.": "",
  "A 30-year-old can buy a $500,000 20-year term life policy for $25/month or a $500,000 whole life policy for $350/month. If they buy term and invest the $325/month difference at 8% annual return for 20 years, approximately how much would the investment grow to?": "",
  "$191,000": "",
  "$325,000": "",
  "$78,000": "",
  "$96,000": "",
  "Using the future value of annuity formula: $325/month for 20 years at 8% annual (0.667% monthly) yields approximately $191,000. This illustrates the 'buy term and invest the difference' strategy.": "",
  "Mike earns $85,000 per year and wants life insurance coverage equal to 10 times his salary. He can get a 20-year term policy for $0.50 per $1,000 of coverage per month. What is his monthly premium?": "",
  "$850": "",
  "$212.50": "",
  "$425": "",
  "$42.50": "",
  "Coverage needed = $85,000 x 10 = $850,000. Number of $1,000 units = 850. Monthly premium = 850 x $0.50 = $425 per month.": "",
  "Amy has auto insurance with 100/300/100 liability limits. She causes an accident injuring three people with medical bills of $120,000, $80,000, and $50,000. How much will her insurance pay for bodily injury?": "",
